LGTM as an initial attempt.  I suspect this is going to require some tuning over time, but the defaults you picked seem reasonabe

As written, for depth = 2, isn't this going to get called multiple times in multiple objects?  That seems like it could run the BMC out of memory as the trees are being built, because the size is only estimated per MultiAsyncResp, which there could be multiple of, right?  Do we need to go back to having a single MultiAsyncResp object, prior to:

https://github.com/openbmc/bmcweb/commit/72c3ae33bd127f8cd5887000a45adf13a56c7582

That's a really good catch.

That commit enables efficient delegation which is an important feature that Google cares about. And even before that commit, we still create multiple AsyncResponse which could still blow up the memory (imagine a flat tree with depth 1 has 1000 URL to expand).

The only way to solve on top of my head is to limit the number of AsyncResponse this MultiAsyncResp creates via a static counter. This is not ideal but safe.

The ideal solution is to add a memory counter in side Crow::Response so that it doesn't allow new response to be created if a fair amount of memory has been used.

I have updated the change. PTAL

> That's a really good catch.
> 
> That commit enables efficient delegation which is an important feature that Google cares about.

I think we can get both behaviors.  I never said nobody cared about the feature, I'm just saying it's pointing out that maybe we need one "main" object instead of many small ones.

> And even before that commit, we still create multiple AsyncResponse which could still blow up the memory (imagine a flat tree with depth 1 has 1000 URL to expand).

I'm a lot less concerned about that.  Each individual AsyncResp is going to be reasonably small, and each handler has some expectation that it enforce some amount of restraint in objects.  Also, in your example, remember, that only one AsyncResponse object is going to be filled in at a time, so even if there's 1000 AsyncResp objects, the moment each one "fills" with data, it will call end(), and won't blow up memory for more than one object at a time.

> 
> The only way to solve on top of my head is to limit the number of AsyncResponse this MultiAsyncResp creates via a static counter. This is not ideal but safe.

I don't think this is a real concern.  AsyncResponse itself is a relatively small object, with just a Response member, and that response member by default construction is also small.  With that said, I wouldn't be against a static counter if we could prove that it was needed.  We do this same pattern other places for things like http connection limits.

> 
> The ideal solution is to add a memory counter in side Crow::Response so that it doesn't allow new response to be created if a fair amount of memory has been used.

I'm not sure I understand this idea.  Crow::Response is supposed to be a response object for Http requests, why would it itself be measuring memory usage?  If a Response object is created inside HttpConnection, that shouldn't be possible to fail (because connections are already limited in other ways), so I don't think this works as stated, but maybe I'm misunderstanding.

> 
> I have updated the change. PTAL

> I'm a lot less concerned about that.  Each individual AsyncResp is going to be reasonably small, and each handler has some expectation that it enforce some amount of restraint in objects.  Also, in your example, remember, that only one AsyncResponse object is going to be filled in at a time, so even if there's 1000 AsyncResp objects, the moment each one "fills" with data, it will call end(), and won't blow up memory for more than one object at a time.

I have replied to this in Discord. There can be cases where multiple AsyncResponse are pending and each of them has a fair amount of data. 

Got a better idea here: execute sub expand query one by one. In this implementation, we will do deep first search for a sub node (e.g., ComputerSystem), then query the next sub node.

I updated the commit message as well.

PTAL.
